{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.05,0.04,0.33,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110603"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"678"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110603"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is admitted to the general medical ward with a one-day history of left-sided abdominal pain. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and atrial fibrillation. Her regular medications include metformin, apixaban, and metoprolol. She does not smoke and rarely drinks alcohol. The duty intern is called to review her as her pain appears to be worsening and she has developed bloody diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min and irregular, blood pressure 104/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft but tender in the left lower quadrant without guarding or rebound tenderness. Bowel sounds are present but reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 14.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 230 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 97 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 55 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen with contrast","Commence oral vancomycin","Administer intravenous hydrocortisone","Urgent surgical review","Flexible sigmoidoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of ischaemic colitis, including sudden onset of abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea in an elderly patient with cardiovascular risk factors. The left-sided abdominal pain is typical, as the left side of the colon is most commonly affected due to its relatively poor blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E. This imaging modality is the preferred diagnostic tool for ischaemic colitis as it can demonstrate bowel wall thickening, mesenteric stranding, and abnormal bowel wall enhancement. It can also help rule out other causes of abdominal pain and assess the extent of the ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA prompt surgical opinion should certainly be sought, but an \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent surgical review\u003C/strong\u003E taking priority over imaging would only be necessary if peritonitis or bowel perforation was suspected. Another reason for an urgent surgical opinion would be evidence of haemodynamic instability. However, the patient is not obviously unstable and the examination findings (soft abdomen without guarding or rebound tenderness) do not suggest these complications are present. The findings on the CT will help determine the rapidity with which a surgical consultation should be sought. If the presumed diagnosis of ischaemic colitis is correct, at the very least there will be thickening of the bowel wall. If more severe changes are seen, such as pneumatosis coli or portal venous gas, then infarction is very likely and the surgical team will need to be involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in diagnosing ischaemic colitis, showing mucosal changes such as oedema, erythema, and ulceration. However, it is generally not the first-line investigation and carries a small risk of perforation in severe cases. CT is preferred as the initial diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing oral vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E colitis was suspected. While this can present with bloody diarrhoea, the sudden onset of left-sided abdominal pain and the patient\u0027s cardiovascular risk factors make ischaemic colitis more likely. Antibiotic therapy should be guided by the results of diagnostic tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in cases of inflammatory bowel disease flares, but is not indicated as the first step in managing suspected ischaemic colitis. Corticosteroids can potentially mask signs of bowel perforation and are not routinely used in the management of ischaemic colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining the CT scan, management would typically involve bowel rest, intravenous fluids, pain management, and close monitoring. Antibiotics may be initiated if there are signs of infection or perforation. Surgical intervention may be necessary in cases of severe ischaemia, perforation, or failure to improve with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ischaemic colitis typically presents with sudden onset of abdominal pain, often in elderly patients with cardiovascular risk factors.","The left side of the colon is most commonly affected in ischaemic colitis due to its relatively poor blood supply.","CT abdomen with contrast is the preferred imaging modality for diagnosing ischaemic colitis."],"references":["Ahmed M. Ischemic bowel disease in 2021. World J Gastroenterol 2021; 27: 4746-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T11:49:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T11:50:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","